<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Sumitso</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Lurker<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Oct 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Those that say they won't play WoW b/c of whatever reason they come up with just boggles me, reminds me of various hollywood types that said they would move out of the US if a certain guy became president.<br />
<br />
Regardless of the knee jerk reactions people give, Furor did have some good points though as is obvious here, many people missed the points he made due to the vehicle he used to present them; I had the same problem with a a guild I lead, I didn't believe in sugar coating things, and sometimes you need to yell to get things done or emphasize with colorful metaphors to get a point across when dealing with a text based environment, if there was a better way to do it or address the issue of leading through text easier anyone that has a few active neurons would heartily do it; saying ok guys um please turn that mob and clerics would you start rotations doesn't exactly get anyone's attention. I was in a guild that was usually 1-2 steps behind what foh was doing, I can understand his annoyance with the encounters as having dealt with them myself.<br />
<br />
To address the idea that furor's viewpoint is only applicable for the (here come the typical labels) uber, high end, power gamers, I am number one, etc etc people take a look at the trickle down effect; those that followed a year or more after to the same raids did not have to deal with the initial problems, bugs, poor itemizations, and so forth as did those who got there first. And there have been other "non-uber" changes that have trickled down from high end raid changes which have been good for everyone. One idea he posted a while back was something I completely agreed with on loot itemization, instead of having items rot due to class specificity of an item, the named mob would drop a token or item which could be turned in to an NPC for an item and nothing would be wasted dropwise. Now I would bet most that have a hate on for furor completely missed the idea he was trying to convey<br />
<br />
Again don't get lost in the vehicle of the message, not everyone is a churchil or blair in delivery of an idea, if you always discount someone's ideas simply b/c you have a dislike for them, be prepared to miss a good idea or clarification or information you might need. Using a webpage as a discourse for relaying ideas is very powerful but tempering the delivery and choosing the manner is important, personally in the realm of EQ, I prefered tigole's presentation over furors.<br />
<br />
and the disclaimer: I don't know furor, don't care to, and could care less if he never posted anything ever again and started a damn fern garden and danced around in a fairy princess dress.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />I don't FA bards or clerics!!<br />
say no to PADD(paladin attention deficit disorder)</div>
	
