<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Otoole Frostypants</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2004<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><b>Written by Furor:</b><br />
So you see, not only are the "Uberguilds" getting shafted in Luclin, the sorry bitch guilds that like to piss and moan about the "Uberguilds" are also getting shafted. Cause I guarantee you if we're being denied content, guess who suffers? The average Joe guy on the street. The same poor schmuck who always suffers. Yea, YOU DUMBASS. Call your congressman.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>And people say he doesn't care about the casual gamers!<br />
<br />
This man's style of writing, while offensive to many, is the only REAL thing that people appear to notice. If you read the above quote, letting the silliness of the wording roll off your back like water on a duck, you will see that HE WAS THE ONE who whined and complained that content was way, way, way out of line for people paying to play a game. He, being in arguably the top guild of ALL servers (contested mainly at the time by Afterlife) was actually making a statement that, in fact, turned out to be rather valid. A lot of people DID NOT enjoy "high end" (and even medium difficulty) Luclin content until AFTER Planes of Power came out. Furor made that comment in the article linked in this thread.<br />
<br />
Furor was aware of the "trickle down" economics of content. Top end "raid guilds" being the first to access ANY difficult content will continue to remain as such no matter what game is made. It's the casual players who will not access that content for some time to come AFTER the hardcore 18 hour a day players do it. It's simple, really. So, this guy--Furor--with his foul mouth and "in your face" style commentary realized that if HIS GUILD was moaning and whining...imagine how incensed the casual gamer will be. Altruistic? Maybe not. Realistic? Hell yeah.<br />
<br />
Again, say what you want about what an azzwipe he is. I don't care. The guy was not an idiot no matter what you say. I don't need altruism in game design. Realism (as far as game goals go) goes a long way, though.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
